<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n26223f"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n26" href="#n26223f">N26 (VI.B.18)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n26all.htm#n26223f"> 223(f)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> ravengod / White Christ / Hughen &amp; Moonen</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">We must remember that they were heathens, making war upon a Christian land, and fighting for Odin and Thor against <mark>White Christ</mark> <font color="green">[n.: An epithet applied by the Norsemen to our Saviour]</font>. Regardless of their former contests in the north itself, the Vikings were now united on these foreign shores by the ties of mutual interest and a common religion; <font color="green">[...]</font>. The eagle had been consecrated to Jupiter by the Romans; among the Northmen the raven was Odin&apos;s (or the Father-of-all&apos;s) sacred bird. One of Odin&apos;s names was therefore &ldquo;Ravnegud&rdquo; (<mark>raven-god</mark>). The ravens <mark>Hugin and Munin</mark> sat on <font color="green">[56]</font> his shoulders, and only flew away to bring him intelligence of what happened in the world. <small> Jens Jacob Asmussen Worsaae, <a name="JJAW1" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#JJAW1"><cite title="source">An Account of the Danes and Norwegians</cite></a> (1852) 56-7</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
